observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE of the Procuring Entity direct the:

a. BAC 
i) to remind prospective bidders during the pre-bid conference of the completeness of information in the required Class "A" documents, particularly the completeness of declared ongoing and awarded but not yet started government and private contracts and the accuracy of declared Net Financial Contracting Capacity (NFCC);


 ii) to require the contractor to commit or assign other qualified personnel and equipment in cases of simultaneous or overlapping projects, to avoid possible delays in the implementation and substandard quality of work.   Otherwise, disqualify non-compliant bidders during bid evaluation or post qualification based on the grounds set under 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;

b. BAC-TWG judiciously conduct post-qualification by verifying, validating, and ascertaining all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid; and ensure that the Post-Qualification Report contains in-depth results on the verification of all requirements by extending the usual post-qualification period;



c. BAC through its BAC Secretariat, to prepare and send the Notification of Bid Submission and ensure that the bidder receive the said document to ensure transparency and accurate representation of the bids submitted; and

d. Municipal Engineer to strengthen the monitoring on the compliance of contractors pertaining to Occupational Safety and Health Standards through frequent inspection of the projects.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:
Municipal Accountant to:
confirm the balance of ₱6,691.89 from the City of Marikina and retrieve the documents pertaining to ₱87,063.34 fund transfers from various benefactors to ascertain if the Municipality has the obligation to return these funds to the source agency otherwise, revert the same to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund;
follow up the PGLU on the MOA or any similar document in order to know the specific purpose, if any, of the fund transferred for winning the Best LGU Christmas Village, and make necessary adjusting entry, if appropriate;
make the necessary adjusting entry debiting Due to LGU amounting to ₱614,501.10, and crediting Prior Period Adjustment and Subsidy from LGU amounting to ₱479,501.10 and ₱135,000.00, respectively;
thereafter, ensure the purpose for the fund transfers received through MOA or other similar documents; and
Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that the remaining balance of fund transfers without specific purpose amounting to ₱614,501.10 be authorized by the Sangguniang Bayan prior to use for implementation of programs, projects, and activities to be determined by the Municipality.

We recommended the LCE:
create an Inventory Committee that shall prepare a PIP containing the specific assignments/duties of the committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start to finish in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
thereafter, enjoin the Inventory Committee, GSO and Municipal Accountant to undertake the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to come up with more reliable account balances to be presented in the financial statements;
direct the GSO and Municipal Accountant to maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, and maintain coordination for the regular reconciliation of PPE records, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Engineer;
direct the GSO to exclude from the RCPPPE those items costing below ₱50,000.00; and
direct the Municipal Engineer to:
furnish the GSO supporting documents for completed projects; and
finalize the report of cost, age and condition of the 13 rehabilitated Local Road Networks from CY 2020 and submit the same to the accountant for derecognition.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Accountant to:
refrain from granting additional cash advances until all previously granted cash advance have been fully liquidated or settled;
discontinue the practice of using cash advances to pay for the procurement of regular repairs and maintenance of motor vehicles, and ensure compliance with the   procurement procedures prescribed under the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
strictly enforce the prescribed liquidation period and require the immediate refund/return of any excess amount thereof; and
implement appropriate measures to strengthen and update existing internal controls, particularly in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
End-users to specify the technical specifications of the items needed in the PR, along with the purpose for which the purchase is requested;
GSO-Designate to:
take in-charge of the systematic numbering and dating of PR, PO and AIR to maintain a clear audit trail and consequently, to enhance procurement efficiency, financial accountability and regulatory compliance;
prepare the PO in accordance with Section 122 of Volume I of the MNGAS to ensure that all required fields in the PO are accurately and completely filled out; and
ensure that the actual date of inspection and date of acceptance are specified to establish clear evidence of when the goods or services are received and whether they meet the required standards.
Bids and Awards Committee to:
use the updated APP template from the GPPB's official website, which specifies the applicable alternative mode of procurement;
if the original mode of procurement cannot be pursued, ensure that a BAC Resolution is prepared, recommending and justifying the changes to the HoPE, in accordance with Section 48.3 of the revised IRR;
prepare and send the RFQs to potential suppliers through the appropriate procurement office instead of the end-user units. Otherwise, issue a resolution delegating this responsibility to the end-user units, subject to approval by the HoPE; and
clearly specify the required information in the RFQs such as the technical specifications, the ABC, delivery period, and price validity period.

We recommended that the LCE direct the AAO and Municipal Accountant to:
exert additional effort to reconcile beginning balances related to prior years’ transactions, including the Due from GOCCs account, and address identified discrepancies for the current year, implement the necessary adjustments and promptly remit any outstanding balances;
coordinate with other responsible officers to ensure immediate updates to employee records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth;
review the monthly premiums deducted from payroll/disbursement vouchers for remittances to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and Philhealth and ensure that amount withheld is the same as the amount required to be remitted monthly; and
strictly abide with the provisions of RA No. 8291, RA No. 9769 and the  Revised IRR of RA No. 7875 in order to avoid administrative sanctions.

We recommended that the LCE direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:

a.	Discontinue the practice of drawing checks payable to one of the payees of the labor payroll, instead, draw checks in favor of the authorized disbursing officer for payments involving several payees or payroll;



b.	Initiate a formal request to the Sangguniang Bayan for authorization to establish a dedicated fund for the Assistance to Individuals in Crisis Situations (AICS) based on the previous year’s transactions;



c.	Designate a separate special disbursing officer for the payment of AICS to reduce the work responsibility of the Acting Municipal Treasurer; and

d.	Ensure that payments must be made directly to the employee or supplier through the issuance of a check or advice to debit account, whichever is applicable, except those expressly allowed under COA Circular No. 97-002. Additionally, withhold mandatory taxes, if applicable.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

All the departments/offices to prepare the RIS for the requested supplies and materials from the GSO Designate;

The GSO – Designate to: prepare the necessary documents such as stock cards and RSMI based on the issued RIS in order to properly monitor the receipt and issuance of inventories;


Conduct actual physical count of inventories and prepare the RPCI pursuant to Section 124 of Chapter VII, Volume I of the NGAS; and

Furnish a copy of the RSMI to the Municipal Accountant which will serve as her basis in the recording of corresponding expenditure accounts and the RPCI.

The Municipal Accountant and GSO – Designate to reconcile their records to ensure check and balance in the receipt and issuance of inventories.

We have recommended that the LCE direct the:

Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant determine, or if not practicable, estimate the carrying amount of the assets replaced taking into consideration the cost, age and condition of the replaced asset;


Thereafter, Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustments in the Local Road Networks account for the derecognition of the replaced assets.;

